<DOC><DOCNO> AP890510-0215 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 2158EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BBCStrike     05-10 0173</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BBC Strike,0180</SECOND><HEAD>BBC Strike Cuts Schedule of Live Programs</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Thousands of journalists, entertainers, andcameramen at the British Broadcasting Corp. stayed off the job forthe second day Wednesday, forcing curtailment or cancellation ofnewscasts and other live programs.   The corporation said 12,000 of its 25,000 workers stayed home onthe second day of the 48-hour walkout. BBC management said it hopedconditions would return to normal Thursday.   All radio and television news programs were cut short.   A live talk show hosted by popular Terry Wogan was replaced witha repeat of an interview with ``Dynasty'' star Joan Collins.   Late-night live pop shows were replaced by pre-recorded material.   It was the second time in three months the unions have struckfor better pay.   They want raises of 16 percent to match salaries in commercialbroadcasting. The BBC, which is funded by public fees, has offered7 percent.   The unions say the national average pay for a BBC journalist is$28,390 a year, compared with $40,080 in commercial broadcasting.</TEXT></DOC>